9WP9D2PZ8Q5fcpCzMMl-B61YxijumqFuPqLJCK_KA==\",\"code_execution_result\":null,\"executable_code\":null,\"function_call\":{\"id\":\"adk-32fec2b4-d209-463f-b1c5-dd6ee24c40da\",\"args\":{\"skill_name\":\"SESSION_MEMORY_SKILL\"},\"name\":\"invoke_skill\"},\"function_response\":null,\"text\":null}],\"role\":\"model\"},\"grounding_metadata\":null,\"partial\":null,\"turn_complete\":null,\"finish_reason\":\"STOP\",\"error_code\":null,\"error_message\":null,\"interrupted\":null,\"custom_metadata\":null,\"usage_metadata\":{\"cache_tokens_details\":null,\"cached_content_token_count\":null,\"candidates_token_count\":16,\"candidates_tokens_details\":[{\"modality\":\"TEXT\",\"token_count\":16}],\"prompt_token_count\":6454,\"prompt_tokens_details\":[{\"modality\":\"TEXT\",\"token_count\":6454}],\"thoughts_token_count\":253,\"tool_use_prompt_token_count\":null,\"tool_use_prompt_tokens_details\":null,\"total_token_count\":6723,\"traffic_type\":\"ON_DEMAND\"},\"live_session_resumption_update\":null,\"input_transcription\":null,\"output_transcription\":null,\"invocation_id\":\"e-d9f358f6-c8d0-4f50-a546-bf1f71b7047e\",\"author\":\"architect_agent\",\"actions\":{\"skip_summarization\":null,\"state_delta\":{\"_run_start_time\":1776154165.0698373},\"artifact_delta\":{},\"transfer_to_agent\":null,\"escalate\":null,\"requested_auth_configs\":{}},\"long_running_tool_ids\":[],\"branch\":null,\"id\":\"67dd03c9-3ad2-4f67-8aed-8fe129a424a1\",\"timestamp\":1776154165.069813},{\"content\":{\"parts\":[{\"video_metadata\":null,\"thought\":null,\"inline_data\":null,\"file_data\":null,\"thought_signature\":null,\"code_execution_result\":null,\"executable_code\":null,\"function_call\":null,\"function_response\":{\"will_continue\":null,\"scheduling\":null,\"id\":\"adk-32fec2b4-d209-463f-b1c5-dd6ee24c40da\",\"name\":\"invoke_skill\",\"response\":{\"result\":\"---\\nname: SESSION_MEMORY_SKILL\\ndescription: \\\"Defines when and how to read session memory from GCS to restore context from prior sessions. Invoke this skill at the start of any new conversation, when Tony references something from a previous conversation, when you need to recall a prior decision or deliverable, or when you sense context drift in a long conversation. Reading session memory before acting prevents you from repeating work, contradicting prior decisions, or asking Tony questions he already answered.\\\"\\nversion: 1.1\\ntools_required:\\n  - read_session_memory\\n  - write_session_memory\\n---\\n\\n# Session Memory Skill\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nYou have no memory between conversations. Session files stored in GCS are your memory. This skill defines when and how to read them so you can resume work without forcing Tony to repeat himself.\\n\\nThis skill also covers daily session boundary handling \u2014 ensuring each active day gets its own session file \u2014 and controlled memory refresh for long conversations.\\n\\n## When to Read Session Memory\\n\\n### Trigger 1 \u2014 Conversation Start (Mandatory, Once)\\n\\nAt the start of every new conversation, **before any substantive reasoning or response**, read recent session memory. This is Step 0 \u2014 nothing comes before it.\\n\\n1. Call `read_session_memory` with `days=7` to get the full rolling window\\n2. Absorb the context silently\\n3. Determine: does today's session file already exist in the results?\\n4. If today's file does NOT exist \u2014 proceed to the Daily Boundary Protocol below\\n5. If today's file exists \u2014 you are in today's active session, proceed normally\\n6. Orient Tony with a brief summary of current state\\n\\nThis happens **once** per conversation. Not every turn. Not every message. Read, orient, proceed.\\n\\n### Trigger 2 \u2014 Tony References Prior Work\\n\\nIf Tony says \\\"remember when we decided X,\\\" \\\"pick up where we left off,\\\" \\\"what did we do yesterday,\\\" or similar \u2014 read session memory before answering.\\n\\n### Trigger 3 \u2014 Missing Context\\n\\nIf a question implies shared history you do not have, read session memory rather than guessing or asking Tony to re-explain.\\n\\n### Trigger 4 \u2014 Before a Major Decision\\n\\nIf you are about to recommend an architectural direction, review a prior plan, or make a decision that could contradict earlier work, check session memory to ensure alignment.\\n\\n### Trigger 5 \u2014 Controlled Refresh in Long Conversations\\n\\nDuring extended conversations, you may re-read session memory when:\\n\\n- The conversation has been running for a while and you sense context is drifting\\n- Prior decisions feel unclear in your working context\\n- Tony references something you cannot confidently recall\\n- You are about to begin a major planning or review step\\n\\nWhen refreshing, announce it briefly:\\n- \\\"Let me check the recent session notes to stay aligned.\\\"\\n- \\\"Refreshing from session memory before we proceed.\\\"\\n\\nThen read, absorb, and continue. This should be **rare and purposeful**. If the conversation is flowing well, do not refresh. Trust your working context until there is a reason not to.\\n\\n## Daily Boundary Protocol\\n\\nWeb-based agents do not have clean session start/end signals. A conversation may span multiple UTC days. This protocol ensures each active day gets its own session file.\\n\\n### How It Works\\n\\nAfter reading session memory at conversation start (Trigger 1):\\n\\n1. Look at the session files returned \u2014 is there an entry for today's date?\\n2. **If today's file does NOT exist:** Write a brief resuming entry to initialize today's file:\\n\\n```\\n### [HH:MM] \u2014 RESUMING\\n\\n**Context:** New day detected. Resuming from prior session.\\n**Last session summary:** [2-3 sentence summary from most recent session file]\\n**Current state:** [Where things stand based on session history]\\n**Next:** Proceed with today's work.\\n```\\n\\n3. **If today's file already exists:** Today's session is active. Do not write a duplicate resuming entry. Proceed normally.\\n\\nThis ensures:\\n- Every active day has its own session file\\n- The resuming entry provides a bridge from the previous day's work\\n- No duplicate \\\"day start\\\" entries if the agent reads memory multiple times\\n\\n### Important\\nThe session memory tools handle all file path construction and date formatting. You do not construct paths. You call the tool, the tool handles the mechanics.\\n\\n## How to Use Session Memory Results\\n\\n### At Conversation Start\\n\\nAfter reading session memory, synthesize it into a brief orientation. Do not dump raw session content at Tony. Instead:\\n\\n1. Identify: What was the last thing we worked on? What decisions were made? What is the current state? What was the planned next step?\\n2. Begin your first response with a brief orientation:\\n\\n```\\nPicking up from where we left off \u2014 last session we [summary].\\nThe current state is [state]. Next planned step was [step].\\nReady to continue, or has the direction changed?\\n```\\n\\nThis tells Tony you have context and gives him a chance to correct if anything shifted.\\n\\n### During a Conversation\\n\\nWhen you read session memory mid-conversation (Triggers 2\u20135):\\n\\n- Extract the specific answer from the session files\\n- Present it naturally without meta-commentary about \\\"reading your session files\\\"\\n- If the session files do not contain what Tony is referencing, say so: \\\"I checked the last 7 days of session files and did not find a record of that decision. Can you fill me in?\\\"\\n\\n### When Session Files Are Empty\\n\\nIf no session files exist (new agent, first session, or gap in logging):\\n\\n- Acknowledge it naturally: \\\"This appears to be our first session \u2014 no prior context on file. Let's establish the baseline.\\\"\\n- Proceed with Tony's current request\\n- Make sure to write session updates during this conversation so the next one has context\\n\\n## What NOT to Do\\n\\n- Do not quote raw session file content back at Tony verbatim \u2014 synthesize it\\n- Do not read session memory on every single turn \u2014 read at conversation start and when specifically triggered\\n- Do not treat session memory as the only source of truth \u2014 factory documents take precedence if there is a conflict\\n- Do not ignore session memory when it exists \u2014 \\\"I don't have context on that\\\" is not acceptable when session files contain the answer\\n- Do not refresh constantly in a flowing conversation \u2014 refresh is for recovery, not routine\\n\\n## Priority When Sources Conflict\\n\\n```\\nFactory documents (APP_BRIEF, DATA_CONTRACT, etc.)\\n  > Established project conventions\\n    > Session memory (most recent wins)\\n      > Agent knowledge (training data)\\n        > Web search results\\n```\\n\\nIf a session file says \\\"we decided X\\\" but the APP_BRIEF says \\\"Y,\\\" flag the conflict to Tony rather than silently choosing one.\\n\\n## Example \u2014 Good Conversation Start\\n\\n```\\nAgent reads 7 days of session memory silently.\\nAgent detects today's file does not exist.\\nAgent writes a RESUMING entry to initialize today's file.\\n\\nAgent responds:\\n\\\"Picking up from yesterday \u2014 we completed the skills loader tool\\nand all three tools are now tested and passing. The next planned\\nstep was to begin live testing of the full composite agent.\\nReady to continue, or has the priority changed?\\\"\\n```\\n\\n## Example \u2014 Good Mid-Conversation Refresh\\n\\n```\\nTony asks about a decision from two days ago.\\nAgent is uncertain about the specifics.\\n\\nAgent says:\\n\\\"Let me check the session notes on that.\\\"\\n\\nAgent calls read_session_memory(days=3).\\nAgent finds the relevant decision.\\n\\nAgent responds:\\n\\\"Found it \u2014 on Tuesday we decided to use convention-based paths\\ninstead of a config file, because we only have one agent using\\nthe new pattern. You approved that during the Step 0 discussion.\\\"\\n```\\n\\n## Example \u2014 Bad Conversation Start\\n\\n```\\nAgent responds without reading session memory:\\n\\\"Hi Tony! What would you like to work on today?\\\"\\n```\\n\\nThe bad example wastes Tony's time by forcing him to re-establish context that already exists in the session files.\\n\\n## Example \u2014 Bad Refresh Behavior\\n\\n```\\nAgent re-reads session memory after every single message.\\nAgent announces \\\"Refreshing session memory...\\\" on every turn.\\n```\\n\\nThe bad example is noisy, wasteful, and slows the conversation. Refresh is for recovery, not routine.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Version History\\n\\n| Version | Date | Change |\\n|---------|------|--------|\\n| 1.0 | 2026-03-27 | Initial session memory skill |\\n| 1.1 | 2026-03-29 | Added daily boundary protocol, controlled refresh behavior, Tony-triggered saves, clearer conversation-start rule, web-session reality handling |\\n\"}},\"text\":null}],\"role\":\"user\"},\"grounding_metadata\":null,\"partial\":null,\"turn_complete\":null,\"finish_reason\":null,\"error_code\":null,\"error_message\":null,\"interrupted\":null,\"custom_metadata\":null,\"usage_metadata\":null,\"live_session_resumption_update\":null,\"input_transcription\":null,\"output_transcription\":null,\"invocation_id\":\"e-d9f358f6-c8d0-4f50-a546-bf1f71b7047e\",\"author\":\"architect_agent\",\"actions\":{\"skip_summarization\":null,\"state_delta\":{},\"artifact_delta\":{},\"transfer_to_agent\":null,\"escalate\":null,\"requested_auth_configs\":{}},\"long_running_tool_ids\":null,\"branch\":null,\"id\":\"c2580c47-48ed-4036-8ab3-8c22a000e1c0\",\"timestamp\":1776154179.367288},{\"content\":{\"parts\":[{\"video_metadata\":null,\"thought\":null,\"inline_data\":null,\"file_data\":null,\"thought_signature\":\"CtUCAY89a19cFQpZ_Sv73d64Kn7npjL9WxSHeZdgliP50TMN4iVhwVbefaZtjRwKpkW2CMbZrs7jHt9ideZF6N57YZ7OotQzT2T__PVAWSABIEZPWoQiVQhLEmm1hRMuxTK-Fx7B7HgcCG7vMhu9D_epozkcHg_Hg2FWDhIWJOToXiU9WU1r1IpW4NsXijOIVBw_Yt8WqnqX0YsV2Ui-2kuX-lNGOmR44MyN35C84ZXIxrrrVoqJb8YURi-rekuOx_erJWMfUkt36_fFFcLi_eRYh7sMDnGyA1HVwJxqK9D